<section id="systems-biology" class="reveal">
  <h2>Systems Biology: Medicine as Process</h2>
  <p>Systems biology offers a framework that aligns with Aristotelian observation and Heraclitean change. It studies the body as a web of interactions—genes, proteins, environment—rather than a sum of discrete units. This isn’t just academic; it’s practical. A systems view accounts for why two people with the same genetic marker might have wildly different health outcomes based on diet or stress.</p>
  <p>The Department of Systems Biology at City of Hope, backed by nearly $5 million in annual grants from the National Institutes of Health and others, exemplifies this shift. Their work suggests a future where medicine prioritizes dynamic processes over static ideals, potentially upending the mechanistic dogma still taught in medical schools.</p>
</section>

<section id="patient-impact" class="reveal">
  <h2>Patients in the Balance: Agency vs. Authority</h2>
  <p>The Platonic legacy often leaves patients sidelined. When health is reduced to abstract models or genetic verdicts, your role shrinks to compliance—follow the protocol, trust the expert. This disempowerment isn’t just philosophical; it’s felt in every rushed consultation where context is ignored for checkboxes.</p>
  <p>A process-oriented approach, inspired by Aristotle or Heraclitus, flips this. If health is a dynamic system, your choices—how you live, eat, cope—become central. Systems biology supports this, suggesting medicine could empower rather than dictate, treating patients as partners in an unfolding story, not cogs in a machine.</p>
  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"If health is a process, not a verdict, patients become partners—not subjects."</p></aside>
</section>

<section id="conclusion" class="reveal">
  <h2>Can Medicine Escape Plato’s Shadow?</h2>
  <p>Western medicine, for all its triumphs, remains tethered to ancient abstractions that prioritize theory over reality, authority over agency. Platonic idealism built a system where credentialed gatekeepers interpret fixed truths—be they humors or genes—often at the expense of the patient’s lived experience. The cost is clear: a reductionist, sometimes dehumanizing approach that struggles to adapt to new evidence like epigenetics or systems interactions.</p>
  <p>Yet alternatives exist. Aristotle’s empirical lens and Heraclitus’s focus on flux point to a medicine of process, not permanence—a vision systems biology is beginning to realize. The question is whether medicine can evolve if it clings to Plato’s shadow. Perhaps the path to a less authoritarian, more human-centered future lies in embracing change itself as the truest form of health.</p>
</section>

